question: How many schools with an average score in Math greater than 400 in the SAT test are exclusively virtual?
evidence: Exclusively virtual refers to Virtual = 'F'
SQL: SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT T2.School) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.Virtual = 'F' AND T1.AvgScrMath > 400

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT T1.cds) FROM satsc.content: SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT T1.cds) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.Virtual = 'F' AND T1.AvgScrMath > 400

SELECT COUNT(T1.CDSCode) FROM schools AS.content: SELECT COUNT(T1.CDSCode) FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T2.AvgScrMath > 400 AND T1.Virtual = 'F'

SELECT COUNT(*) FROM satscores AS T1 INN.content: SELECT COUNT(*) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.AvgScrMath > 400 AND T2.Virtual = 'F'

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT T1.cds) FROM satsc.content: SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT T1.cds) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.AvgScrMath > 400 AND T2.Virtual = 'F'

SELECT COUNT(*) FROM satscores AS T1 INN.content: SELECT COUNT(*) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.Virtual = 'F' AND T1.AvgScrMath > 400

SELECT COUNT(T1.CDSCode) FROM satscores.content: SELECT COUNT(T1.CDSCode) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.AvgScrMath > 400 AND T2.Virtual = 'F'

SELECT COUNT(T1.cds) FROM satscores AS T.content: SELECT COUNT(T1.cds) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.AvgScrMath > 400 AND T2.Virtual = 'F'

question: Please list the codes of the schools with a total enrollment of over 500.
evidence: Total enrollment can be represented by `Enrollment (K-12)` + `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT T2.CDSCode FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` + T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)` > 500

SELECT DISTINCT CDSCode FROM frpm WHERE.content: SELECT DISTINCT CDSCode FROM frpm WHERE `Enrollment (K-12)` + `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)` > 500

question: Among the schools with an SAT excellence rate of over 0.3, what is the highest eligible free rate for students aged 5-17?
evidence: Excellence rate = NumGE1500 / NumTstTakr; Eligible free rates for students aged 5-17 = `Free Meal Count (Ages 5-17)` / `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT MAX(CAST(T1.`Free Meal Count (Ages 5-17)` AS REAL) / T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE CAST(T2.NumGE1500 AS REAL) / T2.NumTstTakr > 0.3

SELECT MAX(F.\"Percent (%) Eligible Free.content: SELECT MAX(F."Percent (%) Eligible Free (Ages 5-17)") FROM frpm AS F INNER JOIN satscores AS S ON F.CDSCode = S.cds WHERE CAST(S.NumGE1500 AS REAL) / S.NumTstTakr > 0.3

SELECT MAX(T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free.content: SELECT MAX(T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (Ages 5-17)`) AS FreeRate FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE CAST(T1.NumGE1500 AS REAL) / T1.NumTstTakr > 0.3

SELECT MAX(T1.`Percent (%) Eligible Free.content: SELECT MAX(T1.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T2.NumGE1500 / T2.NumTstTakr > 0.3

SELECT MAX(T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free.content: SELECT MAX(T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (Ages 5-17)`) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.NumGE1500 / T1.NumTstTakr > 0.3

SELECT MAX(T3.`Percent (%) Eligible Free.content: SELECT MAX(T3.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (Ages 5-17)`) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode INNER JOIN frpm AS T3 ON T1.cds = T3.CDSCode WHERE T1.NumGE1500 / T1.NumTstTakr > 0.3

SELECT MAX(T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free.content: SELECT MAX(T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (Ages 5-17)`) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE CAST(T1.NumGE1500 AS REAL) / T1.NumTstTakr > 0.3

SELECT MAX(f.`Percent (%) Eligible Free.content:
SELECT MAX(f.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (Ages 5-17)`) 
FROM satscores s 
JOIN frpm f 
ON s.cds = f.CDSCode 
WHERE CAST(s.NumGE1500 AS REAL) / s.NumTstTakr > 0.3

SELECT MAX(frpm.`Percent (%) Eligible Fr.content: SELECT MAX(frpm.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (Ages 5-17)`) FROM satscores INNER JOIN frpm ON satscores.cds = frpm.CDSCode WHERE satscores.NumGE1500 / satscores.NumTstTakr > 0.3

SELECT MAX(T3.`Percent (%) Eligible Free.content: SELECT MAX(T3.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (Ages 5-17)`) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode INNER JOIN frpm AS T3 ON T2.CDSCode = T3.CDSCode WHERE T1.NumGE1500 / T1.NumTstTakr > 0.3

SELECT MAX(T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free.content: SELECT MAX(T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (Ages 5-17)`) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.NumGE1500 * 1.0 / T1.NumTstTakr > 0.3

question: Rank schools by their average score in Writing where the score is greater than 499, showing their charter numbers.
evidence: Valid charter number means the number is not null
SQL: SELECT CharterNum, AvgScrWrite, RANK() OVER (ORDER BY AvgScrWrite DESC) AS WritingScoreRank FROM schools AS T1  INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T2.AvgScrWrite > 499 AND CharterNum is not null

SELECT s1.AvgScrWrite, s1.cds, s2.Charte.content: SELECT s1.AvgScrWrite, s1.cds, s2.CharterNum FROM satscores AS s1 INNER JOIN frpm AS s2 ON s1.cds = s2.CDSCode WHERE s1.AvgScrWrite > 499 ORDER BY s1.AvgScrWrite DESC

SELECT T1.CharterNumber, T2.AvgScrWrite.content: SELECT T1.CharterNumber, T2.AvgScrWrite FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T2.AvgScrWrite > 499 AND T1.CharterNumber IS NOT NULL ORDER BY T2.AvgScrWrite DESC

SELECT T1.School, T1.CharterNum FROM sch.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.CharterNum FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T2.AvgScrWrite > 499 AND T1.CharterNum IS NOT NULL ORDER BY T2.AvgScrWrite DESC

question: List the names of schools with more than 30 difference in enrollements between K-12 and ages 5-17? Please also give the full street adress of the schools.
evidence: Diffrence in enrollement = `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT T1.School, T1.Street FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)` > 30

SELECT T1.School, T1.Street FROM schools.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.Street FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)` > 30

SELECT schools.School, schools.Street FR.content: SELECT schools.School, schools.Street FROM schools JOIN frpm ON schools.CDSCode = frpm.CDSCode WHERE (frpm.`Enrollment (K-12)` - frpm.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > 30

question: Give the names of the schools with the percent eligible for free meals in K-12 is more than 0.1 and test takers whose test score is greater than or equal to 1500?
evidence: Percent eligible for free meals = Free Meal Count (K-12) / Total (Enrollment (K-12)
SQL: SELECT T2.`School Name` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE CAST(T2.`Free Meal Count (K-12)` AS REAL) / T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` > 0.1 AND T1.NumGE1500 > 0

SELECT T1.School, T2.`Percent (%) Eligib.content: SELECT T1.School, T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)` FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode INNER JOIN satscores AS T3 ON T1.CDSCode = T3.cds WHERE T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)` > 0.1 AND T3.NumGE1500 > 0

SELECT T3.School FROM satscores AS T1 IN.content: SELECT T3.School FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode INNER JOIN schools AS T3 ON T3.CDSCode = T1.cds WHERE T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)` > 0.1 AND T1.NumGE1500 > 0

SELECT T2.School, T1.NumGE1500 FROM sats.content: SELECT T2.School, T1.NumGE1500 FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode INNER JOIN frpm AS T3 ON T3.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T3.[Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)] > 0.1 AND T1.NumGE1500 > 0

SELECT T2.School, T1.`Percent (%) Eligib.content: SELECT T2.School, T1.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)` FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)` > 0.1 AND T2.CDSCode IN (SELECT T3.cds FROM satscores AS T3 WHERE T3.NumGE1500 > 0)

SELECT T2.School, T3.`Percent (%) Eligib.content: SELECT T2.School, T3.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode INNER JOIN frpm AS T3 ON T3.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T3.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)` > 0.1 AND T1.NumGE1500 >= 1

SELECT T1.School, T3.[Percent (%) Eligib.content: SELECT T1.School, T3.[Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)] FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds INNER JOIN frpm AS T3 ON T1.CDSCode = T3.CDSCode WHERE T3.[Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)] > 0.1 AND T2.NumGE1500 >= 1

SELECT T1.School, T2.NumGE1500 FROM scho.content: SELECT T1.School, T2.NumGE1500 FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds INNER JOIN frpm AS T3 ON T1.CDSCode = T3.CDSCode WHERE T3.[Percent (%) Eligible FRPM (K-12)] > 0.1 AND T2.NumGE1500 > 0

SELECT s.School, f.[Percent (%) Eligible.content: SELECT s.School, f.[Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)] FROM satscores AS s INNER JOIN frpm AS f ON s.cds = f.CDSCode WHERE f.[Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)] > 0.1 AND s.NumGE1500 >= 1

SELECT T1.School, T2.Percent FROM school.content: SELECT T1.School, T2.Percent FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode INNER JOIN satscores AS T3 ON T1.CDSCode = T3.cds WHERE T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)` > 0.1 AND T3.NumGE1500 > 0

SELECT DISTINCT T1.School FROM schools A.content: SELECT DISTINCT T1.School FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds INNER JOIN frpm AS T3 ON T1.CDSCode = T3.CDSCode WHERE T3.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)` > 0.1 AND T2.NumGE1500 >= 1

SELECT T1.School, T2.NumGE1500 FROM scho.content: SELECT T1.School, T2.NumGE1500 FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds INNER JOIN frpm AS T3 ON T1.CDSCode = T3.CDSCode WHERE T3.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)` > 0.1 AND T2.NumGE1500 > 0

SELECT T1.School, T2.[Percent (%) Eligib.content: SELECT T1.School, T2.[Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)] FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T2.numge1500 / NULLIF(T2.NumTstTakr, 0) IS NOT NULL AND T2.numge1500 / NULLIF(T2.NumTstTakr, 0) >= 1500 AND T2.[Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)] > 0.1

SELECT T1.School, T2.Percent FROM school.content: SELECT T1.School, T2.Percent FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode INNER JOIN satscores AS T3 ON T1.CDSCode = T3.cds WHERE T2.Percent > 0.1 AND T3.NumTstTakr >= 1500

SELECT s.School, f.\"Percent (%) Eligibl.content: SELECT s.School, f."Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)", sat.NumTstTakr FROM schools s JOIN frpm f ON s.CDSCode = f.CDSCode JOIN satscores sat ON s.CDSCode = sat.cds WHERE f."Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)" > 0.1 AND sat.NumGE1500 >= 1500

SELECT T3.School, T3.SchoolName FROM sat.content: SELECT T3.School, T3.SchoolName FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode INNER JOIN schools AS T3 ON T2.CDSCode = T3.CDSCode WHERE T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12)` > 0.1 AND T1.NumGE1500 >= 1500

SELECT T2.School, T1.NumGE1500, T2.Perce.content: SELECT T2.School, T1.NumGE1500, T2.Percent_eligible_FRPM_K12 FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.Percent_eligible_FRPM_K12 > 0.1 AND T1.NumGE1500 >= 1500

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?
evidence: Average of average math = sum(average math scores) / count(schools).
SQL: SELECT T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`District Name` LIKE 'Riverside%' GROUP BY T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` HAVING CAST(SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) AS REAL) / COUNT(T1.cds) > 400

SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM sc.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.City = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T1.School HAVING SUM(T2.AvgScrMath) / COUNT(T1.School) > 400

SELECT DISTINCT T2.School, T2.FundingTyp.content: SELECT DISTINCT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T2.School, T1.AvgScrMath HAVING SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) / COUNT(T1.business_id) > 400

SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM sa.content: SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T2.School HAVING AVG(T1.AvgScrMath) > 400

SELECT T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1.content: SELECT T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T1.FundingType HAVING AVG(T2.AvgScrMath) > 400

SELECT DISTINCT T2.FundingType FROM sats.content: SELECT DISTINCT T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.City = 'Riverside' AND T1.AvgScrMath > 400

SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM sc.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' AND T2.AvgScrMath > 400

SELECT DISTINCT T1.FundingType FROM scho.content: SELECT DISTINCT T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' AND T2.AvgScrMath > 400

SELECT T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1.content: SELECT T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T1.FundingType HAVING SUM(T2.AvgScrMath) / COUNT(T2.AvgScrMath) > 400

SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM sa.content: SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Riverside' AND T1.AvgScrMath > 400
SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T2.CDSCode = T1.cds WHERE T2.City = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T2.School, T2.FundingType HAVING AVG(T1.AvgScrMath) > 400
SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T2.School, T2.FundingType HAVING AVG(T1.AvgScrMath) > 400

SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM sc.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.City = 'Riverside' AND T2.AvgScrMath > 400

SELECT T1.School, T2.FundingType FROM sc.content: SELECT T1.School, T2.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T1.School HAVING AVG(T2.AvgScrMath) > 400

SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM sa.content: SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T1.cds HAVING SUM(AvgScrMath) / COUNT(T1.cds) > 400

question: State the names and full communication address of high schools in Monterey which has more than 800 free or reduced price meals for ages 15-17?
evidence: Full communication address should include Street, City, State and zip code if any.
SQL: SELECT T1.`School Name`, T2.Street, T2.City, T2.State, T2.Zip FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Monterey' AND T1.`Free Meal Count (Ages 5-17)` > 800 AND T1.`School Type` = 'High Schools (Public)'

SELECT T3.School, T3.Street, T3.City, T3.content: SELECT T3.School, T3.Street, T3.City, T3.State, T3.Zip FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode INNER JOIN satscores AS T3 ON T2.CDSCode = T3.cds WHERE T1.`Percent (%) Eligible FRPM (Ages 15-17)` > 800 AND T2.City = 'Monterey' AND T2.EILName = 'High School (Public)'

SELECT T2.School, T2.Street, T2.MailCity.content: SELECT T2.School, T2.Street, T2.MailCity, T2.MailZip, T2.MailState FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.`Percent (%) Eligible FRPM (Ages 5-17)` > 0.8 AND T2.City = 'Monterey' AND T2.SOCType = 'High Schools (Public)'

SELECT T1.School, T1.Street, T1.City, T1.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.Street, T1.City, T1.State, T1.Zip FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.State = 'CA' AND T1.City = 'Monterey' AND T2.School_Type = 'High Schools (Public)' AND T2.FRPM Count (Ages 15-17) > 800

SELECT T3.School, T3.Street, T3.City, T3.content: SELECT T3.School, T3.Street, T3.City, T3.State, T3.Zip FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds INNER JOIN schools AS T3 ON T2.cds = T3.CDSCode WHERE T3.County = 'Monterey' AND T3.SOCType = 'High Schools (Public)' AND T1.FRPM Count (Ages 5-17) > 800

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.

question: List the names of virtual schools that are among the top 5 in their respective counties based on average reading scores.

question: Of the schools that offers a magnet program serving a grade span of Kindergarten to 8th grade, how many offers Multiple Provision Types? List the number of cities that offers a Kindergarten to 8th grade span and indicate how many schools are there serving such grade span for each city.
evidence: Kindergarten to 8th grade refers to K-8; 'Offers a magnet program' means Magnet = 1; Multiple Provision Types refers to `NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types'
SQL: SELECT T2.City, COUNT(T2.CDSCode) FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.Magnet = 1 AND T2.GSoffered = 'K-8' AND T1.`NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types' GROUP BY T2.City

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT T1.City) AS cities.content:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT T1.City) AS cities, T1.City, COUNT(*) AS schools 
FROM schools AS T1 
INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode 
WHERE T1.GSoffered = 'K-8' AND T1.Magnet = 1 AND T2.`NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types' 
GROUP BY T1.City

SELECT schools.City, COUNT(schools.CDSCo.content:
SELECT schools.City, COUNT(schools.CDSCode) AS NumberOfSchools 
FROM schools 
INNER JOIN frpm ON schools.CDSCode = frpm.CDSCode 
WHERE schools.GSserved = 'K-8' AND schools.Magnet = 1 AND frpm.`NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types' 
GROUP BY schools.City

SELECT cities.City, COUNT(cities.School).content:
SELECT cities.City, COUNT(cities.School) AS Number_of_Schools 
FROM (
    SELECT DISTINCT S.cds, S.School, S.City 
    FROM frpm as F 
    INNER JOIN schools as S 
    ON F.CDSCode = S.CDSCode 
    INNER JOIN satscores as SS 
    ON SS.cds = S.CDSCode 
    WHERE S.Magnet = 1 
    AND S.GSoffered = 'K-8' 
    AND F.`NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types'
) as cities
GROUP BY cities.City

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?
evidence: Average of average math = sum(average math scores) / count(schools).
SQL: SELECT T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`District Name` LIKE 'Riverside%' GROUP BY T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` HAVING CAST(SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) AS REAL) / COUNT(T1.cds) > 400

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.
evidence: Difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment can be computed by `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T2.DOC FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (SELECT AVG(T3.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T3.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T3 INNER JOIN schools AS T4 ON T3.CDSCode = T4.CDSCode WHERE T4.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType 
FROM schools AS T1 
INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 
ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode 
WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded' 
AND (T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (
    SELECT AVG(T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) 
    FROM schools AS T1 
    INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 
    ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode 
    WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded'
)

question: Among the schools with an SAT excellence rate of over 0.3, what is the highest eligible free rate for students aged 5-17?
evidence: Excellence rate = NumGE1500 / NumTstTakr; Eligible free rates for students aged 5-17 = `Free Meal Count (Ages 5-17)` / `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT MAX(CAST(T1.`Free Meal Count (Ages 5-17)` AS REAL) / T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE CAST(T2.NumGE1500 AS REAL) / T2.NumTstTakr > 0.3

SELECT MAX(T2.`Percent (%) Eligible Free (Ages 5-17)`) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.NumGE1500 / T1.NumTstTakr > 0.3

question: Give the names of the schools with the percent eligible for free meals in K-12 is more than 0.1 and test takers whose test score is greater than or equal to 1500?

SQL: SELECT T2.`School Name` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE CAST(T2.`Free Meal Count (K-12)` AS REAL) / T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` > 0.1 AND T1.NumGE1500 > 0

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?
evidence: Average of average math = sum(average math scores) / count(schools).
SQL: SELECT T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`District Name` LIKE 'Riverside%' GROUP BY T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` HAVING CAST(SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) AS REAL) / COUNT(T1.cds) > 400

SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM sa.content: SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T2.School, T2.FundingType HAVING SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) / COUNT(T1.AvgScrMath) > 400

SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM sa.content: SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T2.School HAVING AVG(T1.AvgScrMath) > 400

SELECT schools.School, schools.FundingTy.content: SELECT schools.School, schools.FundingType FROM schools INNER JOIN satscores ON schools.CDSCode = satscores.cds WHERE schools.County = 'Riverside' AND satscores.AvgScrMath > 400

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.
evidence: Difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment can be computed by `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T2.DOC FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (SELECT AVG(T3.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T3.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T3 INNER JOIN schools AS T4 ON T3.CDSCode = T4.CDSCode WHERE T4.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

SELECT S.School, S.DOCType \nFROM school.content:
SELECT S.School, S.DOCType 
FROM schools S 
JOIN (
    SELECT CDSCode, EnrollmentDifference
    FROM (
        SELECT CDSCode, Enrollment (K-12) - Enrollment (Ages 5-17) AS EnrollmentDifference
        FROM frpm
        WHERE CDSCode IN (
            SELECT CDSCode 
            FROM schools 
            WHERE FundingType = 'Locally funded'
        )
    ) AS subquery
    WHERE EnrollmentDifference > (SELECT AVG(EnrollmentDifference) FROM (
        SELECT CDSCode, Enrollment (K-12) - Enrollment (Ages 5-17) AS EnrollmentDifference
        FROM frpm
        WHERE CDSCode IN (
            SELECT CDSCode 
            FROM schools 
            WHERE FundingType = 'Locally funded'
        )
    ))
) AS FilteredSubquery ON S.CDSCode = FilteredSubquery.CDSCode

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.
evidence: Difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment can be computed by `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T2.DOC FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (SELECT AVG(T3.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T3.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T3 INNER JOIN schools AS T4 ON T3.CDSCode = T4.CDSCode WHERE T4.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

SELECT AVG(Enrollment (K-12) - Enrollment (Ages 5-17)) AS AvgDiff FROM frpm WHERE CDSCode IN (SELECT CDSCode FROM schools WHERE FundingType = 'Locally funded')

WITH AvgDiffCTE AS (
    SELECT AVG(Enrollment (K-12) - Enrollment (Ages 5-17)) AS AvgDiff

)

question: Of the schools that offers a magnet program serving a grade span of Kindergarten to 8th grade, how many offers Multiple Provision Types? List the number of cities that offers a Kindergarten to 8th grade span and indicate how many schools are there serving such grade span for each city.
evidence: Kindergarten to 8th grade refers to K-8; 'Offers a magnet program' means Magnet = 1; Multiple Provision Types refers to `NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types'
SQL: SELECT T2.City, COUNT(T2.CDSCode) FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.Magnet = 1 AND T2.GSoffered = 'K-8' AND T1.`NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types' GROUP BY T2.City

SELECT schools.City, COUNT(schools.City) AS Number_of_Schools 
FROM schools 
JOIN satscores ON schools.CDSCode = satscores.cds 
JOIN frpm ON schools.CDSCode = frpm.CDSCode 
WHERE satscores.GSserved = 'K-8' 
  AND schools.Magnet = 1 
  AND frpm.`NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types' 
GROUP BY schools.City

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?
evidence: Average of average math = sum(average math scores) / count(schools).
SQL: SELECT T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`District Name` LIKE 'Riverside%' GROUP BY T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` HAVING CAST(SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) AS REAL) / COUNT(T1.cds) > 400

SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM sc.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T1.CDSCode HAVING AVG(T2.AvgScrMath) > 400

SELECT T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1.content: SELECT T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.City = 'Riverside' AND T2.AvgScrMath > 400 GROUP BY T1.FundingType

SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM sa.content: SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T2.School HAVING AVG(T1.AvgScrMath) > 400

SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T2.School HAVING SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) / COUNT(T2.School) > 400

SELECT Schools.School, Schools.FundingTy.content:
SELECT Schools.School, Schools.FundingType 
FROM satscores 
JOIN schools ON satscores.cds = schools.CDSCode 
WHERE schools.City = 'Riverside' 
GROUP BY Schools.School, Schools.FundingType 
HAVING AVG(satscores.AvgScrMath) > 400

SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' AND T2.AvgScrMath > 400
SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T1.School HAVING SUM(T2.AvgScrMath) / COUNT(T2.cds) > 400

question: State the names and full communication address of high schools in Monterey which has more than 800 free or reduced price meals for ages 15-17?
evidence: Full communication address should include Street, City, State and zip code if any.
SQL: SELECT T1.`School Name`, T2.Street, T2.City, T2.State, T2.Zip FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Monterey' AND T1.`Free Meal Count (Ages 5-17)` > 800 AND T1.`School Type` = 'High Schools (Public)'

question: What is the average score in writing for the schools that were opened after 1991 or closed before 2000? List the school names along with the score. Also, list the communication number of the schools if there is any.
evidence: Communication number refers to phone number.
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T1.AvgScrWrite, T2.Phone FROM schools AS T2 LEFT JOIN satscores AS T1 ON T2.CDSCode = T1.cds WHERE strftime('%Y', T2.OpenDate) > '1991' OR strftime('%Y', T2.ClosedDate) < '2000'

SELECT T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.School, T1.Pho.content: SELECT T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.School, T1.Phone FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR T1.ClosedDate < '2000-12-31'

SELECT s.School, AVG(sa.AvgScrWrite) AS.content: SELECT s.School, AVG(sa.AvgScrWrite) AS AverageWritingScore, s.Phone FROM schools AS s LEFT JOIN satscores AS sa ON sa.cds = s.CDSCode WHERE s.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR s.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01' GROUP BY s.School, s.Phone

SELECT T1.School, T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.Pho.content: SELECT T1.School, T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.Phone FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.OpenDate > '1991-12-31' OR T1.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'
SELECT T1.School, T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.Phone FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.opendate > '1991-01-01' OR T1.closeddate < '2000-01-01'

FROM schools AS s

WHERE s.OpenDate > '1991-12-31' OR s.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.
evidence: Difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment can be computed by `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T2.DOC FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (SELECT AVG(T3.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T3.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T3 INNER JOIN schools AS T4 ON T3.CDSCode = T4.CDSCode WHERE T4.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

SELECT S.School, S.DOCType \nFROM school.content:
SELECT S.School, S.DOCType 
FROM schools S 
JOIN frpm F ON S.CDSCode = F.CDSCode 
WHERE S.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (F.Enrollment (K-12) - F.Enrollment (Ages 5-17)) > (
    SELECT AVG(K12.Enrollment (K-12) - K12.Enrollment (Ages 5-17)) 
    FROM frpm K12 
    JOIN schools K12S ON K12.CDSCode = K12S.CDSCode 
    WHERE K12S.FundingType = 'Locally funded'
)

SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM school.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)` > (SELECT AVG(`Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm WHERE FundingType = 'Locally funded') AND T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded'

SELECT T2.School, T2.DOCType FROM frpm A.content: SELECT T2.School, T2.DOCType FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > ( SELECT AVG(T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' )

SELECT s.School, s.DOCType \nFROM school.content:
SELECT s.School, s.DOCType 
FROM schools AS s 
INNER JOIN frpm AS f ON s.CDSCode = f.CDSCode 
WHERE f.CHarter School (Y/N) = 0 
AND (f.Enrollment (K-12) - f.Enrollment (Ages 5-17)) > (
    SELECT AVG(f1.Enrollment (K-12) - f1.Enrollment (Ages 5-17)) 
    FROM frpm AS f1

)

question: List the names of virtual schools that are among the top 5 in their respective counties based on average reading scores.
evidence: Exclusively virtual refers to Virtual = 'F'; respective counties means PARTITION BY County
SQL: SELECT School FROM (SELECT T2.School,T1.AvgScrRead, RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY T2.County ORDER BY T1.AvgScrRead DESC) AS rnk FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.Virtual = 'F' ) ranked_schools WHERE rnk <= 5

SELECT s.School, s.County, ss.AvgScrRead.content:
SELECT s.School, s.County, ss.AvgScrRead
FROM schools s
JOIN satscores ss ON s.CDSCode = ss.cds
WHERE s.Virtual = 'F'
ORDER BY s.County, ss.AvgScrRead DESC
LIMIT 5

LIMIT 5

question: Between San Diego and Santa Barbara, which county offers the most number of schools that does not offer physical building? Indicate the amount.
evidence: 'Does not offer physical building' means Virtual = F in the database.
SQL: SELECT County, COUNT(Virtual) FROM schools WHERE (County = 'San Diego' OR County = 'Santa Barbara') AND Virtual = 'F' GROUP BY County ORDER BY COUNT(Virtual) DESC LIMIT 1

SELECT County, COUNT(*) AS TotalSchools.content:
SELECT County, COUNT(*) AS TotalSchools 
FROM schools 
WHERE Virtual = 'F' AND County IN ('San Diego', 'Santa Barbara') 
GROUP BY County 
ORDER BY TotalSchools DESC 
LIMIT 1

question: What is the grade span offered in the school with the highest longitude?
evidence: the highest longitude refers to the school with the maximum absolute longitude value.
SQL: SELECT GSoffered FROM schools ORDER BY ABS(longitude) DESC LIMIT 1

SELECT GSoffered FROM schools ORDER BY A.content: SELECT GSoffered FROM schools ORDER BY ABS(Longitude) DESC LIMIT 1

SELECT GSoffered FROM schools WHERE Long.content: SELECT GSoffered FROM schools WHERE Longitude = (SELECT MAX(ABS(Longitude)) FROM schools)
SELECT GSoffered FROM schools WHERE Longitude = (SELECT MAX(Abs(Longitude)) FROM schools)

SELECT GSoffered FROM schools WHERE ABS(.content: SELECT GSoffered FROM schools WHERE ABS(Longitude) = (SELECT MAX(ABS(Longitude)) FROM schools)

SELECT GSoffered FROM schools ORDER BY I.content: SELECT GSoffered FROM schools ORDER BY IIF(Latitude >= 0, Latitude, Latitude * -1) DESC LIMIT 1

question: Of the schools that offers a magnet program serving a grade span of Kindergarten to 8th grade, how many offers Multiple Provision Types? List the number of cities that offers a Kindergarten to 8th grade span and indicate how many schools are there serving such grade span for each city.
evidence: Kindergarten to 8th grade refers to K-8; 'Offers a magnet program' means Magnet = 1; Multiple Provision Types refers to `NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types'
SQL: SELECT T2.City, COUNT(T2.CDSCode) FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.Magnet = 1 AND T2.GSoffered = 'K-8' AND T1.`NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types' GROUP BY T2.City

SELECT s.City, COUNT(*) AS NumberOfSchoo.content:
SELECT s.City, COUNT(*) AS NumberOfSchools
FROM schools s
JOIN satscores ss ON s.CDSCode = ss.cds
JOIN frpm f ON f.CDSCode = s.CDSCode
WHERE s.Magnet = 1 AND s.GSoffered = 'K-8' AND f.`NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types'
GROUP BY s.City

SELECT s.City, COUNT(*) AS NumSchools, S.content: SELECT s.City, COUNT(*) AS NumSchools, SUM(CASE WHEN f.`NSLP Provision Status` = 'Multiple Provision Types' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS NumMultipleProvisionTypes FROM schools s JOIN frpm f ON s.CDSCode = f.CDSCode WHERE s.GSoffered = 'K-8' AND s.Magnet = 1 GROUP BY s.City

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT T1.city) AS Number.content:

GROUP BY T1.city

question: What is the Percent (%) Eligible Free (K-12) in the school administered by an administrator whose first name is Alusine. List the district code of the school.

question: Among the schools with an SAT excellence rate of over 0.3, what is the highest eligible free rate for students aged 5-17?
evidence: Excellence rate = NumGE1500 / NumTstTakr; Eligible free rates for students aged 5-17 = `Free Meal Count (Ages 5-17)` / `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?

question: What is the average score in writing for the schools that were opened after 1991 or closed before 2000? List the school names along with the score. Also, list the communication number of the schools if there is any.
evidence: Communication number refers to phone number.

question: Among the schools with an SAT excellence rate of over 0.3, what is the highest eligible free rate for students aged 5-17?

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.
evidence: Difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment can be computed by `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`

question: Of the schools that offers a magnet program serving a grade span of Kindergarten to 8th grade, how many offers Multiple Provision Types? List the number of cities that offers a Kindergarten to 8th grade span and indicate how many schools are there serving such grade span for each city.

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.
evidence: Difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment can be computed by `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T2.DOC FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (SELECT AVG(T3.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T3.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T3 INNER JOIN schools AS T4 ON T3.CDSCode = T4.CDSCode WHERE T4.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

SELECT S.School, S.DOCType \nFROM school.content:
SELECT S.School, S.DOCType 
FROM schools S 
JOIN frpm F ON S.CDSCode = F.CDSCode 
WHERE F.Charter = 0 AND (F.`Enrollment (K-12)` - F.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > 
    (SELECT AVG(F2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - F2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) 
     FROM frpm F2 
     JOIN schools S2 ON F2.CDSCode = S2.CDSCode 
     WHERE F2.Charter = 0)

AND FundingType = 'Locally funded'

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?
evidence: Average of average math = sum(average math scores) / count(schools).
SQL: SELECT T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`District Name` LIKE 'Riverside%' GROUP BY T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` HAVING CAST(SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) AS REAL) / COUNT(T1.cds) > 400

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.

question: List the names of virtual schools that are among the top 5 in their respective counties based on average reading scores.
evidence: Exclusively virtual refers to Virtual = 'F'; respective counties means PARTITION BY County

SELECT S.School, S.County, Sc.AvgScrRead

ORDER BY S.County, Sc.AvgScrRead DESC 
LIMIT (SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT County) * 5 FROM schools)

question: What is the total number of non-chartered schools in the county of Los Angeles with a percent (%) of eligible free meals for grades 1 through 12 that is less than 0.18%?

question: Of the schools that offers a magnet program serving a grade span of Kindergarten to 8th grade, how many offers Multiple Provision Types? List the number of cities that offers a Kindergarten to 8th grade span and indicate how many schools are there serving such grade span for each city.

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?
evidence: Average of average math = sum(average math scores) / count(schools).
SQL: SELECT T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`District Name` LIKE 'Riverside%' GROUP BY T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` HAVING CAST(SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) AS REAL) / COUNT(T1.cds) > 400

question: What is the average score in writing for the schools that were opened after 1991 or closed before 2000? List the school names along with the score. Also, list the communication number of the schools if there is any.
evidence: Communication number refers to phone number.
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T1.AvgScrWrite, T2.Phone FROM schools AS T2 LEFT JOIN satscores AS T1 ON T2.CDSCode = T1.cds WHERE strftime('%Y', T2.OpenDate) > '1991' OR strftime('%Y', T2.ClosedDate) < '2000'

SELECT s.School, sats.AvgScrWrite, s.Pho.content: SELECT s.School, sats.AvgScrWrite, s.Phone FROM schools s JOIN satscores sats ON s.CDSCode = sats.cds WHERE s.OpenDate > '1991-12-31' OR s.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

SELECT O.School, O.AvgScrWrite, O.Phone.content: SELECT O.School, O.AvgScrWrite, O.Phone FROM (SELECT T1.School, T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.Phone, T1.OpenDate, T1.ClosedDate FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds) O WHERE O.OpenDate > '1991-12-31' OR O.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

SELECT s.School, AVG(ss.AvgScrWrite) AS.content:
SELECT s.School, AVG(ss.AvgScrWrite) AS Average_Writing_Score, s.Phone AS Communication_Number
FROM schools s
JOIN satscores ss ON s.CDSCode = ss.cds
WHERE s.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR (s.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01' AND s.ClosedDate IS NOT NULL)
GROUP BY s.School, s.Phone

SELECT AVG(AvgScrWrite) AS AvgWritingSco.content:
SELECT AVG(AvgScrWrite) AS AvgWritingScore, s.School, s.Phone AS CommunicationNumber 
FROM satscores ss 
JOIN schools s ON ss.cds = s.CDSCode 
WHERE s.OpenDate > '1991-12-31' OR s.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01' 
GROUP BY s.School, s.Phone

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.
evidence: Difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment can be computed by `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T2.DOC FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (SELECT AVG(T3.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T3.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T3 INNER JOIN schools AS T4 ON T3.CDSCode = T4.CDSCode WHERE T4.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?
evidence: Average of average math = sum(average math scores) / count(schools).
SQL: SELECT T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`District Name` LIKE 'Riverside%' GROUP BY T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` HAVING CAST(SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) AS REAL) / COUNT(T1.cds) > 400

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.
evidence: Difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment can be computed by `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T2.DOC FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (SELECT AVG(T3.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T3.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T3 INNER JOIN schools AS T4 ON T3.CDSCode = T4.CDSCode WHERE T4.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.
evidence: Difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment can be computed by `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?
evidence: Average of average math = sum(average math scores) / count(schools).
SQL: SELECT T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`District Name` LIKE 'Riverside%' GROUP BY T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` HAVING CAST(SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) AS REAL) / COUNT(T1.cds) > 400

SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM sa.content: SELECT T2.School, T2.FundingType FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T2.School HAVING SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) / COUNT(T1.cds) > 400

SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM sc.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T1.School HAVING SUM(T2.AvgScrMath) / COUNT(T2.cds) > 400
SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T1.School HAVING AVG(T2.AvgScrMath) > 400
SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T2.AvgScrMath > 400 AND T1.County = 'Riverside'

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT T1.School), T1.Fun.content: SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT T1.School), T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' GROUP BY T2.AvgScrMath HAVING T2.AvgScrMath > 400

question: State the names and full communication address of high schools in Monterey which has more than 800 free or reduced price meals for ages 15-17?
evidence: Full communication address should include Street, City, State and zip code if any.
SQL: SELECT T1.`School Name`, T2.Street, T2.City, T2.State, T2.Zip FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'Monterey' AND T1.`Free Meal Count (Ages 5-17)` > 800 AND T1.`School Type` = 'High Schools (Public)'

question: What is the average score in writing for the schools that were opened after 1991 or closed before 2000? List the school names along with the score. Also, list the communication number of the schools if there is any.
evidence: Communication number refers to phone number.
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T1.AvgScrWrite, T2.Phone FROM schools AS T2 LEFT JOIN satscores AS T1 ON T2.CDSCode = T1.cds WHERE strftime('%Y', T2.OpenDate) > '1991' OR strftime('%Y', T2.ClosedDate) < '2000'

SELECT T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.School, T1.Pho.content: SELECT T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.School, T1.Phone FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR T1.ClosedDate < '2000-12-31'

SELECT T2.School, T1.AvgScrWrite, T2.Pho.content: SELECT T2.School, T1.AvgScrWrite, T2.Phone FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR T2.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

SELECT T1.School, T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.Pho.content: SELECT T1.School, T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.Phone FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR T1.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

SELECT T2.School, T1.AvgScrWrite, T2.Pho.content:
SELECT T2.School, T1.AvgScrWrite, T2.Phone 
FROM satscores AS T1 
INNER JOIN schools AS T2 
ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode 
WHERE T2.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR T2.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

SELECT AVG(T2.AvgScrWrite) AS AverageWri.content: SELECT AVG(T2.AvgScrWrite) AS AverageWritingScore, T2.sname AS SchoolName, T1.Phone AS CommunicationNumber FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR T1.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01' GROUP BY T2.sname, T1.Phone

SELECT T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.School, T1.Pho.content: SELECT T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.School, T1.Phone FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR T1.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

SELECT T2.AvgScrWrite, T2.sname, T1.Phon.content: SELECT T2.AvgScrWrite, T2.sname, T1.Phone FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR T1.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

SELECT S.School, AVG(AvgScrWrite) AS Ave.content: SELECT S.School, AVG(AvgScrWrite) AS AverageWritingScore, S.Phone FROM satscores AS T INNER JOIN schools AS S ON T.cds = S.CDSCode WHERE S.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR S.ClosedDate < '2000-12-31' GROUP BY S.School, S.Phone

SELECT T1.school, T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.Pho.content: SELECT T1.school, T2.AvgScrWrite, T1.Phone FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.OpenDate > '1991-12-31' OR T1.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

SELECT s.School, ss.AvgScrWrite, s.Phone.content:
SELECT s.School, ss.AvgScrWrite, s.Phone 
FROM schools s 
JOIN satscores ss ON s.CDSCode = ss.cds 
WHERE s.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR s.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.
evidence: Difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment can be computed by `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T2.DOC FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (SELECT AVG(T3.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T3.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T3 INNER JOIN schools AS T4 ON T3.CDSCode = T4.CDSCode WHERE T4.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM school.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > ( SELECT AVG(T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType \nFROM scho.content:
SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType 
FROM schools AS T1 
INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 
ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode 
WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND 
      (T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > 
      (SELECT AVG(`Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) 
       FROM frpm)

SELECT S.School, S.DOCType FROM schools.content: SELECT S.School, S.DOCType FROM schools S INNER JOIN frpm F ON S.CDSCode = F.CDSCode WHERE S.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (F.Enrollment__K_12_ - F.Enrollment__Ages_5_17_) > (SELECT AVG(F2.Enrollment__K_12_ - F2.Enrollment__Ages_5_17_) FROM frpm F2 INNER JOIN schools S2 ON F2.CDSCode = S2.CDSCode WHERE S2.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

SELECT T2.School, T2.DOCType \nFROM frpm.content:
SELECT T2.School, T2.DOCType 
FROM frpm AS T1 
INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode 
WHERE (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (
    SELECT AVG(T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) 
    FROM frpm AS T1 
    INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode 
    WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded'
) 
AND T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded'

SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM school.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Directly funded' AND (T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (SELECT AVG(`Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm)

SELECT schools.School, schools.DOCType F.content: SELECT schools.School, schools.DOCType FROM schools JOIN frpm ON schools.CDSCode = frpm.CDSCode WHERE frpm."Enrollment (K-12)" - frpm."Enrollment (Ages 5-17)" > ( SELECT AVG("Enrollment (K-12)" - "Enrollment (Ages 5-17)") FROM frpm WHERE frpm."FundingType" = 'Locally funded' ) AND schools.FundingType = 'Locally funded'

SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM school.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T2.[Enrollment (K-12)] - T2.[Enrollment (Ages 5-17)]) > ( SELECT AVG([Enrollment (K-12)] - [Enrollment (Ages 5-17)]) FROM frpm WHERE CDSCode IN (SELECT CDSCode FROM schools WHERE FundingType = 'Locally funded') )

SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > ( SELECT AVG(T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded' )

SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T2.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T2.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > ( SELECT AVG(`Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm )

SELECT T2.School, T2.DOCType FROM frpm A.content: SELECT T2.School, T2.DOCType FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (SELECT AVG(T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

question: Name schools in Riverside which the average of average math score for SAT is grater than 400, what is the funding type of these schools?
evidence: Average of average math = sum(average math scores) / count(schools).
SQL: SELECT T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.`District Name` LIKE 'Riverside%' GROUP BY T1.sname, T2.`Charter Funding Type` HAVING CAST(SUM(T1.AvgScrMath) AS REAL) / COUNT(T1.cds) > 400

SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM sc.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.FundingType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN satscores AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.cds WHERE T1.County = 'Riverside' AND T2.AvgScrMath > 400

question: What is the average score in writing for the schools that were opened after 1991 or closed before 2000? List the school names along with the score. Also, list the communication number of the schools if there is any.
evidence: Communication number refers to phone number.
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T1.AvgScrWrite, T2.Phone FROM schools AS T2 LEFT JOIN satscores AS T1 ON T2.CDSCode = T1.cds WHERE strftime('%Y', T2.OpenDate) > '1991' OR strftime('%Y', T2.ClosedDate) < '2000'

SELECT s.School, s.Phone, sat.AvgScrWrit.content:
SELECT s.School, s.Phone, sat.AvgScrWrite 
FROM schools AS s 
INNER JOIN satscores AS sat ON s.CDSCode = sat.cds 
WHERE s.OpenDate > '1991-01-01' OR s.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

SELECT s.School, sa.AvgScrWrite, s.Phone.content: SELECT s.School, sa.AvgScrWrite, s.Phone FROM schools AS s INNER JOIN satscores AS sa ON s.CDSCode = sa.cds WHERE s.OpenDate > '1991-12-31' OR s.ClosedDate < '2000-01-01'

question: Consider the average difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment of schools that are locally funded, list the names and DOC type of schools which has a difference above this average.
evidence: Difference between K-12 enrollment and 15-17 enrollment can be computed by `Enrollment (K-12)` - `Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`
SQL: SELECT T2.School, T2.DOC FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T1.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T1.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) > (SELECT AVG(T3.`Enrollment (K-12)` - T3.`Enrollment (Ages 5-17)`) FROM frpm AS T3 INNER JOIN schools AS T4 ON T3.CDSCode = T4.CDSCode WHERE T4.FundingType = 'Locally funded')

SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM school.content: SELECT T1.School, T1.DOCType FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded' AND (T2.Enrollment__K_12__) - (T2.Enrollment__Ages_5_17__) > ( SELECT AVG((T2.Enrollment__K_12__) - (T2.Enrollment__Ages_5_17__)) FROM schools AS T1 INNER JOIN frpm AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T1.FundingType = 'Locally funded' )

question: What is the average number of test takers from Fresno schools that opened between 1/1/1980 and 12/31/1980?
evidence: between 1/1/1980 and 12/31/1980 means the year = 1980
SQL: SELECT AVG(T1.NumTstTakr) FROM satscores AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.cds = T2.CDSCode WHERE strftime('%Y', T2.OpenDate) = '1980' AND T2.County = 'Fresno'

question: What are the valid e-mail addresses of the administrator of the school located in the San Bernardino county, City of San Bernardino City Unified that opened between 1/1/2009 to 12/31/2010 whose school types are public Intermediate/Middle Schools and Unified Schools?
evidence: Intermediate/Middle Schools refers to SOC = 62; Unified School refers to DOC = 54; years between 2009 and 2010 can refer to 'between 1/1/2009 to 12/31/2010'
SQL: SELECT T2.AdmEmail1, T2.AdmEmail2 FROM frpm AS T1 INNER JOIN schools AS T2 ON T1.CDSCode = T2.CDSCode WHERE T2.County = 'San Bernardino' AND T2.City = 'San Bernardino' AND T2.DOC = 54 AND strftime('%Y', T2.OpenDate) BETWEEN '2009' AND '2010' AND T2.SOC = 62
